<paragraph blockId="8.[140,1108,1117,1672]" pageId="8" pageNumber="127">
The tiger beetle fauna of Arabia has been fairly intensively studied with separate recent coverage of 
<collectingCountry box="[274,350,1153,1179]" name="Yemen" pageId="8" pageNumber="127">Yemen</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Wranik W &amp; Materlik B &amp; Cassola F" box="[366,586,1152,1179]" pageId="8" pageNumber="127" pagination="266 - 272" refId="ref5894" refString="Wranik W, Materlik B, Cassola F (1991) The Cicindelidae (Coleoptera) of the Republic of Yemen. Fauna of Saudi Arabia 12: 266 - 272." type="journal article" year="1991">Wranik et al. 1991</bibRefCitation>
), 
<collectingCountry box="[607,680,1152,1178]" name="Oman" pageId="8" pageNumber="127">Oman</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Cassola F &amp; Rihane A" box="[696,990,1152,1179]" pageId="8" pageNumber="127" pagination="196 - 205" refId="ref5329" refString="Cassola F, Rihane A (1996) Notes on the tiger beetle fauna of the Sultanate of Oman (Coleoptera: Cicindelidae). Fauna of Saudi Arabia 15: 196 - 205." type="journal article" year="1996">Cassola and Rihane 1996</bibRefCitation>
) and eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[184,330,1187,1213]" name="Saudi Arabia" pageId="8" pageNumber="127">Saudi Arabia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Cassola F &amp; Schneider W" box="[345,669,1187,1214]" pageId="8" pageNumber="127" pagination="247 - 253" refId="ref5364" refString="Cassola F, Schneider W (1997) Tiger beetles (Coleoptera: Cicindelidae) from the Saudi Arabian gulf coast. Fauna of Saudi Arabia 16: 247 - 253." type="journal article" year="1997">Cassola and Schneider 1997</bibRefCitation>
) adding to older records from the Red Sea area of 
<collectingCountry box="[272,419,1223,1249]" name="Saudi Arabia" pageId="8" pageNumber="127">Saudi Arabia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Britton EB" box="[436,592,1223,1249]" pageId="8" pageNumber="127" pagination="87 - 131" refId="ref5287" refString="Britton EB (1948) Expedition to South-west Arabia, 1937 - 8. 10: Coleoptera: Cicindelidae and Carabidae (with Appendix by P. Basilewsky). British Museum (Natural History) 1: 87 - 131." type="journal article" year="1948">Britton 1948</bibRefCitation>
). Neither has the 
<collectingCountry box="[800,857,1223,1249]" name="United Arab Emirates" pageId="8" pageNumber="127">UAE</collectingCountry>
been neglected, since separate studies have dealt with its inland (
<bibRefCitation author="Gillett MPT" box="[631,774,1258,1285]" pageId="8" pageNumber="127" pagination="13 - 16" refId="ref5496" refString="Gillett MPT (1995) An annotated and illustrated checklist of tiger beetles from the Al Ain / Buraimi region of Eastern Arabia (Coleoptera: Cicindelidae). Tribulus 5 (2): 13 - 16." type="journal article" year="1995">Gillett 1995</bibRefCitation>
) and coastal cicindelid fauna (
<bibRefCitation author="Wiesner J" box="[147,313,1293,1319]" pageId="8" pageNumber="127" pagination="249 - 260" refId="ref5844" refString="Wiesner J (1993) Uber die Cicindelidae (Coleoptera) der Vereinigten Arabischen Emirate. Entomologische Zeitschrift 103: 249 - 260." type="journal article" year="1993">Wiesner 1993</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Wiesner J" box="[328,391,1293,1320]" pageId="8" pageNumber="127" pagination="382 - 384" refId="ref5868" refString="Wiesner J (1996) Weitere Mitteilungen uber die Cicindelidae (Coleoptera) der Vereinigten Arabischen Emirate. Entomologische Zeitschrift 106: 382 - 384." type="journal article" year="1996">1996</bibRefCitation>
). To date, a total of just 19 species from nine different genera are known from the whole of Arabia, suggesting that because of the size and habitat diversity of the peninsula, further species might occur.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="127" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="8.[140,1108,1117,1672]" pageId="8" pageNumber="127">
One such has recently turned up on Reem Island, right next door to the burgeoning metropolis of 
<collectingRegion box="[353,486,1434,1460]" country="United Arab Emirates" name="Abu Zaby" pageId="8" pageNumber="127">Abu Dhabi</collectingRegion>
, on a site scheduled for massive urban development. Two examples of this very pretty diminutive tiger beetle were collected at a mercury vapour light trap by BH on the 
<date box="[496,727,1504,1530]" pageId="8" pageNumber="127" value="2007-09-03">3rd September 2007</date>
(
<figureCitation box="[742,809,1504,1530]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="9.[140,212,804,826]" captionTargetBox="[140,1108,165,784]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[140,1108,162,787]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figure 4. Callytron monalisa. A living specimen of Callytron monalisa, one of two specimens collected by B. Howarth in 2007 on Reem Island, Abu Dhabi. This rare species is known only from the Iranian side of the Arabian Gulf (photograph by D. Gardner)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3767385" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3767385/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="127">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). The beetle was identified by Cassola, and a manuscript to record this species from the 
<collectingCountry box="[851,908,1540,1566]" name="United Arab Emirates" pageId="8" pageNumber="127">UAE</collectingCountry>
is in preparation (Cassola et al., in press). This represents an amazing new record and range extension of a beetle only previously recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[618,664,1610,1636]" name="Iran" pageId="8" pageNumber="127">Iran</collectingCountry>
on the other side of the Arabian Gulf. Unfortunately, it will likely very soon disappear along with its habitat.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
